##The "travel problem" under the blockade and the people in urgent need of hospital

Micro-signal. NBWEEKLY

Introduction of function, new media with temperature

It's been a week since the siege. Traffic stops in the city, motor vehicle central city limits, so that this modern city used to cars, subway travel people suddenly into a difficult position.

By Chen Xingmeng, Xue Yufei, Xie Chan, Gao Yijia

Editor | Roo

It has been a week since the city of Wuhan was closed at 10 o'clock on January 23. The city's traffic suspension and restrictions on motor vehicles in the city center have put people accustomed to the car and subway suddenly in a tight spot.

Need to go to and from work of the medical staff, the need for regular dialysis patients with uremia, acute attacks need to go to the hospital... Individuals in desperate need of transportation turn to help, and travel problems of all kinds that had not previously been considered become a problem.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
On January 25, the first day of the Lunar New Year, the Huangpu Road subway station in Hankou, Wuhan, was closed. (Source: China Daily. Com)

In order to facilitate Dialysis Hotel, two days hungry to lose two kilograms

Tian Lei, a 40-year-old uremic patient, needs four-hour dialysis three times a week. He used to go to the Concorde Hospital, 30 kilometers away from home, for dialysis. It's a bit far, but it's a ten-minute walk and an hour by subway. But on Jan. 23, after Tian Lei left the hospital for Dialysis, Wuhan was closed to public transportation, and it took him five hours to get home by bike sharing and walking across the Qingchuan Bridge and Yangtze River Bridges.

After this walk, Tian Lei, who has no private car, decided to stay in a hotel near the hospital. The room rate is 120 yuan a day, which is about the same as usual, he said, and may even be lower because there are no outsiders staying. But for most dialysis patients who don't have a job or an income, hotel accommodation is a luxury.

However, New Year's Eve just stayed in a hotel for a day, Tian Lei because the hotel closed, was expelled. He had to find another hotel. There weren't many hotels open.

Likewise, restaurants and shops are closing. Staying alone in a hotel, three Meals a Day has become Tian Lei's biggest problem: "there is no refrigerator in the room, and there will be no food to eat tomorrow. I can only find what I can eat. ". The hospital is the worst affected area, and the cafeteria is only for medical care. I take my weight every time I have dialysis, and I have lost two kilograms on New Year's Eve and the first day of the Lunar New Year."

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
January 26, Wuhan Second Ring Road Zhuyeshan overpass section of the road not many cars. (Source: China Daily. Com)

Like Tian Lei, there are many patients who can not get regular dialysis because of traffic problems, but not many who choose to stay in hotels. "Most of the rich have cars, and most of the people who don't have cars have no money to drive. The financial pressure of staying in hotels is too great. Some people struggle by walking and sharing bicycles, while others choose to seek help from the community, " Tian said.

Tian Lei says many patients now go to dialysis in a car sent by the community. But different communities have different situations, some communities can't offer a car service: "It's too far, " he says. Second Hospital, for example. Nanjing Road's on 24-hour dialysis, but there's no car at night. There are three types of Car Service: Volunteer Service, community service and self-paid car service.

Tian also worries about elderly uremic patients who need a wheelchair to help them walk. They often have little social contact and do not join a well-informed group of patients, which can be more dangerous if they live alone.

Patients with acute enteritis struggle to find a car

January 28 at 3:00 pm, nest at Home Online Zhou Jie suddenly felt severe abdominal pain. She hasn't been out much since the city was shut down in Wuhan, but she still goes out occasionally to buy food. The thought of this, coupled with the fact that she had been suffering from a sore throat for several days and was now feverish, made her wonder if she was suffering from COVID-19? She quickly put on the mask and told her mother to put on the mask and stay away from her.

After two hours of pain did not improve, one side of the mother can not help anxious. She called 120 for an ambulance, but she couldn't get through, and she couldn't get through to 110.

At 5:30 p.m. , Zhou Jie was too sore to type. She asked her friends to help her find a friend's circle of friends, and asked about nearby cars in the volunteer group. Soon many drivers in the group of Volunteers Volunteer volunteer driver initiative to ask, but they that time is picking up and sending medical staff at the high-speed port, too far to catch up.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
On January 28, the Wuhan Yangtze River Railway Tunnel between Macau road and Wuchang in Hankou was closed. (Source: China Daily. Com)

At 6 pm, a friend sent her the community car phone, the community after the call to calm her down and soon find a car to come. In this way, after three hours of physical and psychological torture, Zhou Jie finally boarded the car on the road to the hospital.

Arriving at the hospital, Zhou Jie, who had a fever of 38 degrees, was first sent to the fever clinic for a screening of pneumonia, and then to the emergency department for a CT and blood drawing. After tossing around until 8 p.m. , the doctor's preliminary diagnosis was acute enteritis. Only then did Zhou Jie feel at ease, took the medicine and went home to rest.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
A reminder from Zhou Jie to her friends after her illness

On the way home, the driver told Zhou Jie that he was also a volunteer. After the community posted a message asking for help in a car on the wechat group at that time, many volunteers rushed to sign up to pick up patients because they were relatively close, so he put down his bowl and set off.

Folk caring motorcade helps solve the commuting problem of medical staff

On January 23, Wuhan was sealed off, and on January 24, Li Dong gathered a group of people to take care of the task of transporting medical staff to and from work. The timely response and self-help of all sectors of society brought a glimmer of hope to a city beset by an epidemic. According to local media, more than 4,000 car owners have spontaneously joined various charity motorcades through the call of local civic organizations.

However, after only one day of operation, at 16:00 on the 25th, the Wuhan COVID-19 Epidemic Prevention and Control Headquarters issued a notice No. 9, announcing that in addition to licensed Baogong transport vehicles, free transport vehicles and official vehicles, the central urban area shall implement the administration of banning motor vehicles from driving.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
On January 24th, on the eve of the Lunar New Year, at 3 pm, there were few pedestrians in front of the Wuhan Optics Valley F.C. . (Source: China Daily. Com)

After receiving the news, Li Dong posted a notice in the wechat group named "Wuhan pick-up and drop-off, " informing everyone that starting tomorrow, the work of the convoy of caring pick-up and drop-off medical personnel can come to an end. "Maybe the official manpower is in place, and we don't need our people power, so we can rest at home, " Li said.

Several of the nurses in the group began to worry about how to get to work the next day. The question had been in front of them since the siege of Wuhan. After the city's public transport is shut down, how to get around seems to be a battle between time and money costs. For health care workers without private cars and other epidemic prevention workers who must be on duty, the only options left to them are walking and cycling.

Late on the night of January 25, the Wuhan Traffic Control Bureau gave an urgent explanation: Vehicles Not used for epidemic prevention and control work will be banned from traffic management, through the form of mobile phone text messages 24 hours in advance to inform car owners, motor vehicles that have not been notified by SMS may pass. Violators will be severely punished up to 12 points.

Some owners have been waiting until the wee hours of the morning, did not receive a text message notice, just relax. In a city where public transport has been suspended, it is hard to imagine what would happen if private cars were banned and motorcades stopped.

Phil Chang is one of the owners of Li Dong's caring motorcade. In the Group of the motorcade, the volunteer will update and sort out the needs of the medical staff who need to travel. If he sees someone who is able to help, he will contact them according to the information left by the volunteer. In one day, he picked up and sent three medical staff, they all came back from outside of Wuhan to work at the hospital.

It was agreed that the hitchhiker's medical staff would provide gloves, alcohol, 84 disinfectant and hydrogen peroxide to help disinfect the car. Phil Chang said that before picking up and dropping off passengers, he would wipe the seats and door knobs with alcohol and leave at least 15 minutes to ventilate the car.

On the afternoon of the 26th, Didi APP developed the function of online car-hailing for medical staff only. As of 18:30 pm on the 28th, the platform had been connected to 3,713 health care workers in nine districts of seven hospitals in Wuhan.

Nurses on leave from other places hope to return to Wuhan for support, waiting for no car

Li Fei, a nurse at a hospital in Wuhan, had returned to her hometown in Xiangyang normally on leave from work. After the outbreak she wanted to return to support Wuhan, but how to return to become a problem. Li Fei asked for help on Weibo, facebook and Wechat, hoping for a ride back to Wuhan, but she couldn't find a car until it was time to go back to work in Wuhan.

Song Hong, a nurse in Zhijiang, faced the same dilemma. In Zhijiang, too, vehicle restrictions are in place, and she has been unable to get a response to her hopes of finding a similar supply truck from Zhijiang to take her back to the city for support.

In addition to not having a car, Li Fei faces other obstacles. According to regulations, the Wuhan motorcade vehicles can only drive from the city to the Wuhan Highway Junction, and medical personnel to provide proof can pass. Li Fei said her certificate, which previously required one stamp and then another, had not yet been processed.

"No. 8 Order" issued, the community car has a different explanation

Xu Hao and her husband are working in the hospital, this year did not go home for the Spring Festival, has been waiting for the dispatch, ready where to go. Because the home is in the far city of Wuhan, originally wanted to apply for coordination with the head nurse to work in the branch hospital closer to home, but the branch hospital has sufficient medical staff, and now the headquarter is understaffed, she must go to the headquarter.

After hearing that each community will be equipped with 3-5 cars, she has called the community for three consecutive days, and later to the municipal government, the response is that there are not enough cars, even if there is a work permit and related certification is useless. There was no response from the Volunteer Motorcade Group, and her certification on Didi's platform has yet to be approved. Xu Good told reporters, the group did not pass the certification of colleagues there are many, in order to find a car, worried her a few nights can not sleep.

On January 24, the headquarters issued an order No. 8, announcing that every community in the central city area would be equipped with 3 -- 5 vehicles, mainly to solve the problems such as the inaccessibility of residents'homes. But the use of these vehicles varies from community to community.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
(Source: The Voice of Hubei)

A community secretary in Hanyang District told reporters that the taxis, which deliver vegetables, medicines and meals to residents, usually do not deliver people, but also help medical staff when there is a need for transport.

Another community leader said that the taxis allocated by the community mainly provide convenience for the disadvantaged groups in the district and the elderly and infirm residents who are not able to travel, such as the lonely and lonely elderly and the empty-nest elderly, or as an emergency. These cars are not designed to solve the travel problem of health care workers. Health care workers themselves may carry germs, and if the germs remain in the car, they are likely to infect other passengers. "medical personnel should have a special vehicle to pick them up. "

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
January 28, the central city area after the implementation of the ban on motor vehicles. The city urgent collection of 6000 taxis, distributed to the central city, by the community residents unified dispatch. (Source: China Daily. Com)

Finally Xu good finally contact a colleague with a car, she intends to pack up at home directly drag a suitcase to the hospital, and then live over there not to come back. "Of course, living at home is relatively safe, and my husband and I are isolated enough. But there's no way, get over it. " She said with a wry smile.

"Traffic Control has had a big impact on our citizens. There are many pregnant women waiting to give birth in the community, dialysis patients who don't have a car, and they are in a much more urgent situation than we are, so leave the car to the people who need it the most. "

(at the request of the interviewees, the names in this article are all pseudonyms. Feng Jie and Li Xujin also contributed to this article.)
